</span> traveling through the medium in opposite directions. A generalized representation of this wave can be obtained<sup about="#mwt340" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-5" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-5"}}'><a href="./Wave#cite_note-5" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 5;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[5]</span></a></sup> as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Partial_differential_equation" title="Partial differential equation" id="mwiw">partial differential equation</a></p>

<dl id="mwjA"><dd id="mwjQ"><span class="mwe-math-element" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt288" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"\n\\frac{1}{v^2}\\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial t^2}=\\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial x^2}. \\,\n"}}' id="mwjg"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle {\frac {1}{v^{2}}}{\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}}}={\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}}.\,}">
